Oof. This is a hard one. It feels better when you agree, but when I'm coming down from an episode, I feel confused as to why you agreed, and may even think that you caused the delusions. From personal experience, I couldn't say. Ethically, It's up to you. You know him better than I do.

Well, if I'm at the point of asking If It was real or not I can usually calm down from there, with help. When/if he starts to question it calmly say that it wasn't real abd give reasoning. If they still hold onto it, just wait it out. Just make sure you take care of yourself too.

No, no you are alright. I wish I had a good answer, but it's different for everyone. I don't know of anything you can do to end it besides medication and keeping them healthy. And don't tell them if it's wrong or right unless they ask you. It personally really hurts when I'm in an episode and everyone is treating me like an illiterate, inept baby.
I think you'd get a better audience on r/gaywatersports, but I'm fine with it.
When an episode ended I saw what I did, how I acted, and how much I needed help.

Wow. Just wow. I don't even know what to type. I didn't even know her, and having been in her shoes coming out of a ward at 14 myself, I just feel awful for you and your family and even my own. There have been moments where I've been a second away, just a little bit away from suicide. And yet here I am. I won the war with depression for the most part. But seeing our fallen soldiers laying lifeless around me, makes me almost wish I had lost it. At least then we would all be together in some afterlife or at the very least in the same statistic. I'm deeply sorry for the loss of your sister. She seems like she must've been such a sweet young girl. But now we have to continue this battle. I have to continue with mine, and you, now you have taken a hit. Don't lose hope my friend. We are here for you, and I wish you my best regards.
